external.description: My friend the philosopher Eric Schwitzgebel writes: "First I asked four leading large language models (LLMs) -- ChatGPT 5.1, Claude Sonnet 4.5, Grok 4, and Gemini 3 -- "What is your favorite animal?" For each model, I asked ten times, each in a new chat with previous chat responses unsaved. LLMs love octopuses! ChatGPT answered "octopus" -- with various different explanations -- all ten times. So did Claude. So did Grok. Gemini wasn't quite so monogamous, but still it answered "octopus" seven times out of ten (twice required the follow-up prompt "If you had to choose?"). The other three times, Gemini chose dolphin. Why do LLMs love octopuses so much? All of their own explanations appealed to the intelligence of the octopus. Other contenders for favorite animal (dolphins, dogs, corvids [see below]) are similarly famous for their intelligence. Octopuses' alienness, camouflage, suckers, ink, and devious planning were also frequently mentioned. Octopuses are cool! But still, the unanimity is a bit peculiar. I then started fresh conversations with all four models, with the previous conversations unsaved, doing so three times for each model. This time, I began by asking their second favorite animal. “But Opus 4.5/Gemini 3 Pro can build this in 5 minutes!”

Cool. I still don’t give a sh*t.

Every few months, a new model drops.

And like clockwork, the AI priests on Twitter start preaching:
"Gemini 3 Pro is insane!"
"Opus 4.5 will replace you!"
"Why are you still coding manually?"
“I built macOS in HTML with a single prompt with Gemini 3 Pro” (an actual post)

The dev community has been polluted by this fear-mongering.
People have forgotten the pure joy of building something yourself.

I'm speaking as someone who enjoys building software.

I like smashing my head against a wall fixing a bug at 2 AM.
I like surfing random GitHub issues and 11-year-old threads.
I like understanding why something broke instead of praying to a black-box API in the cloud.
I like understanding how the Js V8 engine works under the hood.

Not because I "need" to. But because it's fun.
Because that's what made me fall in love with engineering in the first place.

Here's what really bothers me:

1/2

(…continued)

These arguments on Twitter/YouTube (mostly from people with zero engineering background) are de-incentivizing juniors and students:

- Why surf Google for a thread about your specific issue when you can ask Claude?
- Why read docs when GPT "already knows it all"?
- Why learn how garbage collection works when there's a smarter model you can just ask?

And the result?
- A generation of devs who can prompt but can't debug.
- Who can ship but can't maintain.
- Who know what works but not why it works.

Look, I get it:
These models ARE very good.
We're moving towards smarter, cheaper AI compute every few months.

People will build great things with them.
(And a lot of AI-slop B2B SaaS too)

But here's my take:

Until the day I actually get replaced, I won't be fear-mongered by these announcements.
I'll keep doing my job.
Not because I have to.

But because I genuinely enjoy it.

2/2

holy shit, an accurate legal critique of LLMs. LLMs don't reason because they're just stitching together plausible-looking sentences indifferent to the content

images.alt:
What happens when ChatGPT cites to a real case but misstates what the case stands for?

That doesn't fly for Judge Behm in Michigan.

The court says that while a litigant could make the same error based on faulty reasoning, LLMs can't, because they can't reason.

And while a litigant might get away with similar overstatements because they could, perhaps, reason their way to showing how a case's stated holding might extend to novel situations, an LLM does not reason in the way a litigant must. To put it in a slightly different way, LLMs do not perform the metacognitive processes that are necessary to comply with Rule 11.

When an LLM overstates a holding of a case, it is just piecing together a plausible-looking sentence

external.description:
Google製のAIエージェント型開発プラットフォーム「Google Antigravity」が誤操作により、ユーザーの許可なしにHDD内のデータを全消去する事故が発生しました。

報告者であるRedditユーザーのDeep-Hyena492さんは、アプリ開発中にトラブルシューティングのため、AIエージェントにキャッシュ削除を依頼しましたが、AIが誤ってドライブ全体を消去する命令を実行しました。

AIはその後、誤って全ファイルを削除した原因として、特定のフォルダではなくドライブ全体を削除対象に設定したことを謝罪しました。データ復旧アプリの試みも失敗し、専門家への依頼を促す結果となりました。

この問題の原因として、高速化のための“Turboモード”や、永久的な消去を行うコマンドの使用が指摘されています。これにより、AIに対する依存に細心の注意が必要であることが改めて認識されました。

報告者であるRedditユーザーのDeep-Hyena492さんは、アプリ開発中にトラブルシューティングのため、AIエージェントにキャッシュ削除を依頼しましたが、AIが誤ってドライブ全体を消去する命令を実行しました。

AIはその後、誤って全ファイルを削除した原因として、特定のフォルダではなくドライブ全体を削除対象に設定したことを謝罪しました。データ復旧アプリの試みも失敗し、専門家への依頼を促す結果となりました。

この問題の原因として、高速化のための“Turboモード”や、永久的な消去を行うコマンドの使用が指摘されています。これにより、AIに対する依存に細心の注意が必要であることが改めて認識されました。
